CSE 5324:Shenxiao Mei, Samuel Lefcourt

In this lab, we will use a dataset of images of hand gesture. There are 10 different gestures representing 0-9 numbers.Sign languages (also known as signed languages) are languages that use manual communication to convey meaning. This can include simultaneously employing hand gestures, movement, orientation of the fingers, arms or body, and facial expressions to convey a speaker's ideas. Since our dataset only contains the number digits sign from 0-9, we would consider our model can be used as a starting point for a mobile app which teaches people sign language. Users can take photos of their hand gesture and upload in the app, where our model will identify the hand gesture to see if it is correct. As a starting point of the recognization app, our model needs to perform very well in differentiating the digits sign in order to be useful.

In terms of standard of success, we need to compare our model accuracy in recognization with the real human sign interpreters. In http://d-scholarship.pitt.edu/8488/1/SadlerKarenL20509.pdf, there is a research conducted to find out the accuracy human interpreter in tranlating science words into signs in a science videos. The result shows that the interpretation are roughly 80% correct. Since our model only recognize digits,which is a lot easier task than translating science knowledge. Also, our accuracy needs to be very high in order to conduct future work, we set our standard to be 95% correct.


Kaggle Source: https://www.kaggle.com/ardamavi/sign-language-digits-dataset

Metrics Selection

In this lab for our model we decide to use accuracy. Since our model will serve as a feasibility study of a hand gesture recognization app, and it only identify sign digits, accuracy can be used as a perfect metrics for us to know if the model performs well enough for the app developer to move on to the next stage (recognize character). We need to compare our model's accuracy to a professional interpreter's accuracy in order to determine whether our model is successful.

Data Split

In our model we will use a stratified kfold cross validation. Since our dataset has only 2000 thousand samples for ten digits, 200 hundred images per digit, if we perform a normal 80/20 split, it is likely that we selected twenty percent of unrepresentative samples. We use 10 folds in our model because the amount of 10 is widely known as the optimal number of folds in machine learning.

In [38]:
img_wh =  64
NUM_CLASSES = 10

# fix size
from sklearn.model_selection import StratifiedKFold
import keras

cv=StratifiedKFold(n_splits=10, shuffle=True)

X_train_list=[]
X_test_list=[]
y_train_list=[]
y_test_list=[]
y_train_ohe_list=[]
y_test_ohe_list=[]

label = []
for i in range(len(y)):
    label.append(np.argmax(y[i]))    
y = np.asarray(label)

for train_index, test_index in cv.split(X, y):
#     print("TRAIN: ", train_index,"\n", "TEST: ", test_index, "\n")
    X_train, X_test = X[train_index], X[test_index]
    y_train, y_test = y[train_index], y[test_index]
    y_train_ohe = keras.utils.to_categorical(y_train, NUM_CLASSES)
    y_test_ohe = keras.utils.to_categorical(y_test, NUM_CLASSES)
    X_train = np.expand_dims(X_train.reshape((-1,img_wh,img_wh)), axis=3)
    X_test = np.expand_dims(X_test.reshape((-1,img_wh,img_wh)), axis=3)
    
    X_train_list.append(X_train)
    X_test_list.append(X_test)
    y_train_list.append(y_train)
    y_test_list.append(y_test)
    y_train_ohe_list.append(y_train_ohe)
    y_test_ohe_list.append(y_test_ohe)

Data Expansion

Since we are using kfold cross validation methods, it is better to create a function that will return a new ImageDataGenerator object to fit with new data every time.

In our data expansion, we will use rotation_range. In our business case, when people do hand gesture, it is very likely they don't have the perfect angle, having rotation should help with our training. We are use width shift and height shift just in case the hand gesture may have shifts in the location.

Overall, since each hand gesture has only 200 images, we use data generator not only to reduce the noise of shifts and rotation, we can reduce the chance of overfitting.

In [39]:
import keras
from keras.preprocessing.image import ImageDataGenerator

def get_datagen():
    datagen = ImageDataGenerator(featurewise_center=False,
        samplewise_center=False,
        featurewise_std_normalization=False,
        samplewise_std_normalization=False,
        zca_whitening=False,
        rotation_range=5, # used, Int. Degree range for random rotations.
        width_shift_range=0.1, # used, Float (fraction of total width). Range for random horizontal shifts.
        height_shift_range=0.1, # used,  Float (fraction of total height). Range for random vertical shifts.
        shear_range=0., # Float. Shear Intensity (Shear angle in counter-clockwise direction as radians)
        zoom_range=0.,
        channel_shift_range=0.,
        fill_mode='nearest',
        cval=0.,
        horizontal_flip=True,
        vertical_flip=False,
        rescale=None)
    return datagen

Modeling

For modeling, since we have 10 folds for each model, we will create two lists which store the y prediction and histories for future analysis

CNN Model 1

For the first Model, we will use two convolutional layers in which the filter number is same. In each convolutional layer we will use a three by three kernel, a relu activation function and a max pooling. Then it will pass through a fallten layer and two layer of 100 perceptrons.

In [41]:
from keras.models import Sequential
from keras.layers import Dense, Dropout, Activation
from keras.optimizers import SGD
from keras.layers import Dense,Flatten,Dropout,Concatenate,GlobalAveragePooling2D,Lambda,ZeroPadding2D
from keras.layers import SeparableConv2D,BatchNormalization,MaxPooling2D,Conv2D

cnn1 = Sequential()

num_filt_layers = [24, 24]
for num_filters in num_filt_layers:
    cnn1.add(Conv2D(filters=num_filters, 
                   input_shape=(64, 64, 1), 
                   kernel_size=(3,3), 
                   padding='same', 
                   activation='relu'))
    cnn1.add(Activation('relu'))
    cnn1.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2), data_format="channels_first"))
    

# add one layer on flattened output
cnn1.add(Flatten())
cnn1.add(Dense(100, activation='relu'))
cnn1.add(Dense(100, activation='relu'))
cnn1.add(Dense(10, activation='softmax'))

# Let's train the model 
cnn1.compile(loss='categorical_crossentropy',
              optimizer='rmsprop',
              metrics=['accuracy'])
In [42]:
import keras.backend as K
def reset_weights(model):
    session = K.get_session()
    for layer in model.layers: 
        if hasattr(layer, 'kernel_initializer'):
            layer.kernel.initializer.run(session=session)
In [43]:
%%time

y_pred_cnn1_list=[]
history_cnn1_list=[]
for i in range(len(X_train_list)):
    datagen_1=get_datagen()
    history=cnn1.fit_generator(datagen_1.flow(X_train_list[i], y_train_ohe_list[i], batch_size=32),
                             steps_per_epoch=int(X_train_list[i].shape[0]/64),
                             epochs=80, verbose=1,
                               validation_data=(X_test_list[i], y_test_ohe_list[i])
                             )
    y_pred_cnn1 = cnn1.predict(X_test_list[i]).ravel()
    y_pred_cnn1_list.append(y_pred_cnn1)
    history_cnn1_list.append(history)
    reset_weights(cnn1)

CNN Model 2

In the CNN model, we did a slight change on parameters on the convultional layer. We change the kernel size to 2x2.

In [12]:
cnn2 = Sequential()

num_filt_layers = [24, 24]
for num_filters in num_filt_layers:
    cnn2.add(Conv2D(filters=num_filters, 
                   input_shape=(64, 64, 1), 
                   kernel_size=(2,2), 
                   padding='same', 
                   activation='relu'))
    cnn2.add(Activation('relu'))
    cnn2.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2), data_format="channels_first"))
    

# add one layer on flattened output
cnn2.add(Flatten())
cnn2.add(Dense(100, activation='relu'))
cnn2.add(Dense(100, activation='relu'))
cnn2.add(Dense(10, activation='softmax'))

# Let's train the model 
cnn2.compile(loss='categorical_crossentropy',
              optimizer='rmsprop',
              metrics=['accuracy'])
In [ ]:
%%time

y_pred_cnn2_list=[]
history_cnn2_list=[]
for i in range(len(X_train_list)):
    datagen_2=get_datagen()
    history=cnn2.fit_generator(datagen_2.flow(X_train_list[i], y_train_ohe_list[i], batch_size=32),
                             steps_per_epoch=int(X_train_list[i].shape[0]/64),
                             epochs=80, verbose=1,
                               validation_data=(X_test_list[i], y_test_ohe_list[i])
                             )
    y_pred_cnn2 = cnn2.predict(X_test_list[i]).ravel()
    y_pred_cnn2_list.append(y_pred_cnn2)
    history_cnn2_list.append(history)
    reset_weights(cnn2)

CNN Model 3

This model's prototype is Model 1, but in this model, we change the filter to three and the filter number

In [41]:
cnn3 = Sequential()

num_filt_layers = [24, 32, 48]
for num_filters in num_filt_layers:
    cnn3.add(Conv2D(filters=num_filters, 
                   input_shape=(64, 64, 1), 
                   kernel_size=(3,3), 
                   padding='same', 
                   activation='relu'))
    cnn3.add(Activation('relu'))
    cnn3.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2), data_format="channels_first"))
    

# add one layer on flattened output
cnn3.add(Flatten())
cnn3.add(Dense(100, activation='relu'))
cnn3.add(Dense(100, activation='relu'))
cnn3.add(Dense(10, activation='softmax'))

# Let's train the model 
cnn3.compile(loss='categorical_crossentropy',
              optimizer='rmsprop',
              metrics=['accuracy'])
In [42]:
%%time

y_pred_cnn3_list=[]
history_cnn3_list=[]
for i in range(len(X_train_list)):
    datagen_3=get_datagen()
    history=cnn3.fit_generator(datagen_3.flow(X_train_list[i], y_train_ohe_list[i], batch_size=32),
                             steps_per_epoch=int(X_train_list[i].shape[0]/64),
                             epochs=80, verbose=1,
                               validation_data=(X_test_list[i], y_test_ohe_list[i])
                             )
    y_pred_cnn3 = cnn3.predict(X_test_list[i]).ravel()
    y_pred_cnn3_list.append(y_pred_cnn3)
    history_cnn3_list.append(history)
    reset_weights(cnn3)

CNN Model 4

This model also has three layers of filters. We change the kernel size from 3x3 to 2x2

In [43]:
cnn4 = Sequential()

num_filt_layers = [24, 32, 48]
for num_filters in num_filt_layers:
    cnn4.add(Conv2D(filters=num_filters, 
                   input_shape=(64, 64, 1), 
                   kernel_size=(3,3), 
                   padding='same', 
                   activation='relu'))
    cnn4.add(Activation('relu'))
    cnn4.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2), data_format="channels_first"))
    

# add one layer on flattened output
cnn4.add(Flatten())
cnn4.add(Dense(100, activation='relu'))
cnn4.add(Dense(100, activation='relu'))
cnn4.add(Dense(10, activation='softmax'))

# Let's train the model 
cnn4.compile(loss='mean_squared_error',
              optimizer='rmsprop',
              metrics=['accuracy'])
In [44]:
%%time

y_pred_cnn4_list=[]
history_cnn4_list=[]
for i in range(len(X_train_list)):
    datagen_4=get_datagen()
    history=cnn4.fit_generator(datagen_4.flow(X_train_list[i], y_train_ohe_list[i], batch_size=32),
                             steps_per_epoch=int(X_train_list[i].shape[0]/64),
                             epochs=80, verbose=1,
                               validation_data=(X_test_list[i], y_test_ohe_list[i])
                             )
    y_pred_cnn4 = cnn4.predict(X_test_list[i]).ravel()
    y_pred_cnn4_list.append(y_pred_cnn4)
    history_cnn4_list.append(history)
    reset_weights(cnn4)

Fight with MLP

In [52]:
mlp = Sequential()
mlp.add( Dense(input_dim=64*64, units=100, activation='relu') )
mlp.add( Dense(units=50, activation='relu') )
mlp.add( Dense(units=50, activation='relu') )
mlp.add( Dense(NUM_CLASSES) )
mlp.add( Activation('softmax') )

mlp.compile(loss='categorical_crossentropy',
              optimizer='rmsprop',
              metrics=['accuracy'])



y_pred_mlp_list=[]
for i in range(len(X_train_list)):
    X_train_alt=X_train_list[i].reshape(X_train_list[i].shape[0],64*64)
    X_test_alt=X_test_list[i].reshape(X_test_list[i].shape[0],64*64)

    datagen_5=get_datagen()
    mlp.fit(X_train_alt, y_train_ohe_list[i], 
        batch_size=32, epochs=80, 
        shuffle=True, verbose=1,
       validation_data=(X_test_alt, y_test_ohe_list[i]))
    y_pred_mlp = mlp.predict(X_test_list[i].reshape(X_test_list[i].shape[0],64*64)).ravel()
    y_pred_mlp_list.append(y_pred_mlp)
    reset_weights(mlp)

y_10_fold=np.zeros(len(y_test_ohe_list[0].flatten()))
y_pred_cnn1=np.zeros(len(y_pred_cnn1_list[0]))
y_pred_cnn2=np.zeros(len(y_pred_cnn2_list[0]))
y_pred_cnn3=np.zeros(len(y_pred_cnn3_list[0]))
y_pred_cnn4=np.zeros(len(y_pred_cnn4_list[0]))
y_pred_mlp=np.zeros(len(y_pred_mlp_list[0]))
for i in range(10):
    y_pred_cnn1=np.concatenate((y_pred_cnn1,y_pred_cnn1_list[i]), axis=0)
    y_pred_cnn2=np.concatenate((y_pred_cnn2,y_pred_cnn2_list[i]), axis=0)
    y_pred_cnn3=np.concatenate((y_pred_cnn3,y_pred_cnn3_list[i]), axis=0)
    y_pred_cnn4=np.concatenate((y_pred_cnn4,y_pred_cnn4_list[i]), axis=0)
    y_pred_mlp=np.concatenate((y_pred_mlp,y_pred_mlp_list[i]), axis=0)
    y_10_fold=np.concatenate((y_10_fold,y_test_ohe_list[i].flatten()),axis=0)

from matplotlib import pyplot as plt
from sklearn.metrics import roc_curve

plt.figure(figsize=(20,10))

color = ['yellow', 'red', 'pink','grey','purple']

# for_roc=y_test_ohe.flatten()
# y_pred_keras_1 = cnn1.predict(X_test).ravel()
fpr_keras_1, tpr_keras_1, thresholds_keras = roc_curve(y_10_fold, y_pred_cnn1)
fpr_keras_2, tpr_keras_2, thresholds_keras = roc_curve(y_10_fold, y_pred_cnn2)
fpr_keras_3, tpr_keras_3, thresholds_keras = roc_curve(y_10_fold, y_pred_cnn3)
fpr_keras_4, tpr_keras_4, thresholds_keras = roc_curve(y_10_fold, y_pred_cnn4)
fpr_mlp, tpr_mlp, thresholds_mlp = roc_curve(y_10_fold, y_pred_mlp)


from sklearn.metrics import auc
auc_keras_1 = auc(fpr_keras_1, tpr_keras_1)
auc_keras_2 = auc(fpr_keras_2, tpr_keras_2)
auc_keras_3 = auc(fpr_keras_3, tpr_keras_3)
auc_keras_4 = auc(fpr_keras_4, tpr_keras_4)


auc_mlp = auc(fpr_mlp, tpr_mlp)

i=0
plt.plot([0, 1], [0, 1], 'k--')
plt.plot(fpr_keras_1, tpr_keras_1, label='CNN Model1 (area = {:.3f})'.format(auc_keras_1),color=color[i])
i+=1
plt.plot(fpr_keras_2, tpr_keras_2, label='CNN Model2 (area = {:.3f})'.format(auc_keras_2),color=color[i])
i+=1
plt.plot(fpr_keras_3, tpr_keras_3, label='CNN Model3 (area = {:.3f})'.format(auc_keras_3),color=color[i])
i+=1
plt.plot(fpr_keras_4, tpr_keras_4, label='CNN Model4 (area = {:.3f})'.format(auc_keras_4),color=color[i])

plt.plot(fpr_mlp, tpr_mlp, label='MLP (area = {:.3f})'.format(auc_mlp))

plt.xlabel('False positive rate')
plt.ylabel('True positive rate')
plt.title('ROC curve')
plt.legend(loc='best')
plt.show()

In this section, we used macro averaging to plot our models' performance on multiclass prediction task. From the plot, we find that MLP has the smallest area, no suprise. For the four models we created, model 1(2 filters, 3x3 kernal) and model 2(2 filters, 2x2 kernal) performs worse than model 3(3 filters, 3x3 kernal) and model 4(3 filters, 2x2 kernal). That means more filters result in better true positive rate. Between Model 3 and model 4 we can see they are overlapping.

Visualize the final results of the CNNs and interpret the performance.

We use the t-distribution with 95% confidence, we will then check if the range of their difference cover 0, if it cover zero, we cannot say they are statisitically different from one and another

    yhat_conc = y_pred_cnn1_list[i].reshape(210,10)
    yhat_conc = np.argmax(yhat_conc, axis=1)

From the heat map we see that model 1 and model 2 have trouble identifying the number '3', that is because all signs of 3,6,7,8,9 have three fingers but different combination of thumbs. Model 3 and model 4 perform uniformly well on all classes.
